Sur years have passed,-a long time for a boy and a

dog: 'Bob Ainslie is off to the wars; I am a medical .

student, and clerk at Minto House Hospital.

Rab 1 saw almost every week, on the Wednesday3 and we had much pleasant intimacy. I found the way to his heart by frequent scratching of his huge head, and an occasional bone. When I did not notice him he would plant himself straight before me, and stand wagging that bud of a tail, and looking up, with his head a little to the one side. His master I occasionally saw3 he used to call me ‘Maister John,' but was laconic as any Spartan.

One line October aftemoon, I was leaving the hospital, when I saw the large gate open, and in walked Rab, with that great and easy saunter of his. He looked as if taking general possession of ¹the place ; like the Duke of Wellington entering a suh dued city, satiated with victory and peace. After him came Jess, now white from age, with her cart ; and in it a woman carefully wrapped up,—the carrier leading the horse anxiously, and looking back.
